*Single Feature MVP*
Prototype in parallel with the Upstream pilot
2/June/2021

We will develop the Single Feature _Research_ of Lefthoek’s tools. By developing this Single Feature we want to demonstrate (through 3 case scenarios or stories) the extent of Lefthoek’s capabilities, this Single Feature must be able to represent ‘the bigger picture’. Jan Hein will build the technology behind it and Elisa will do the user research. These are some of the questions or challenges we will address:
-What do people find useful in the data that we can extract?
-What is the reason they get this tool?
-What features do they need?
-What mediums can we use (articles, texts, videos, podcasts)?
-What language? What values?

---
title: Moonshooters, Fruit-Pickers, and Laika's
order: 1
author: Nato
date: 2021-03-25
tags:
  - moonshots
  - exponentiality
  - entrepreneurship
  - low-hanging fruit
excerpt: |
  In our current society, we use certain labels to identify ourselves and
  manoeuvre in this vast and dynamic world. Labels help us navigate the
  different contexts active in our modern society. Moreover, these labels are
  now more so propagated on the worldwide web as a tool to brand ourselves with
  or amongst others, in the diverse online communities. Consequently, this how
  the ideals of digital citizenship were born. Have a read and see wich persona
  you identify with the most!
---

As we gear-up for the incoming 4th Industrial Revolution, a large part of our
society have take on key roles as we more into a more tech-driven era. Whether
directly or indirectly, you are a participant in this monumental shift in
society. Here at Lefthoek we try understand our society through 5 different
personas. Taking into consideration both the past and present experiences that
has led us all to this forthcoming era, we believe we all had a part to play.
*The question is, what digital citizen do you identify yourself as?* Your label
is fluid and can evolve with the changing times, but  which persona you relate
the most with currently ?

***Dreamers*** are individuals who I think have always been present in society.
These individuals learn about life quickly and eventually find the current state
of affairs mundane. They tend to grow big dreams in mind and aim to obtain the
fruit at the top of the tree. This metaphor is telling to their aims and goals
but also foreboding the high risk they are willing to take. The fruits at the
top of the tree are hard to obtain and they are not always ripe. Visionaries are
willing to risk it all to realise their dreams. One prime example of a visionary
today is Elon Musk. Musk is determined to take humans to wifi0-working Mars in
the next few years. Will this dream materialise, we shall only wait and see... 

![Telescopes](/images/telescopes.jpg)

***Laika*** was one the first animals that were sent to explore space. Retrieved
as a stray dog from the streets of Moscow, she became the first dog to explore
space under the notable Soviet space envoy Sputnik 2 in 1957.  [This notion is
still practiced
today](<https://www.businessinsider.nl/animals-nasa-russia-space-agencies-sent-to-space-2019-6?international=true&r=US#:~:text=Countries%20including%20the%20US%2C%20the,send%20animals%20into%20orbit%20today.>)
but might sound incredulous to some and many may even be inclined to call on
PETA. Nevertheless, this was an insightful feat to the information that was
gathered during the Space race era. During the Cold War, the space race pushed
visionaries/dreamers and fellow politicians to align their ideals to achieve
huge leaps in terms of space exploration. This collaboration then brought about
new key players, such as Laika, that provided society with much insight with the
trajectory they were heading with. Laikas are not intentional players, they are
random intermediaries that factually illustrate the possibilities and the
limitations society, through trial and error. Laikas were the one's who take the
driver's seat. They are and continue to be the failed encounters that teach us
something valuable about our dreams. They provide insights and lesson's learnt.

***Moonshooters*** can be characterized as the over-ambitious cousins of
visionaries, armed with awareness, time and money. This title was ["first
introduced in Jules Verne’s From the Earth to the Moon but popularized by
president John F. Kennedy in
1961.](<https://www.lefthoek.com/blog/the-low-end-theory/>)" Moonshooters are
passionate about solving the world's current wicked problems but fail to
understand that the input of other disciplines and expertise is necessary. Also
it is important to note that not all the of the problems in the 21st century can
be solved through technology. Like the name suggests, "moonshot" conveys an idea
or ideal that is a 'long-shot'. It is something that has a high probability to
not work and this is stemmed from the fact that moonshot projects are done
without any prior, concrete research of potential risks and benefits. The
moonshooter label falls on those those who are doers rather than thinkers and
act fast. Much like the visionaries that dream big, they take it step further
and try to realise the actual project as soon as possible. They are the big
risk-takers, willing to act then later find out the barriers or issues that are
present. 

***Passengers*** are individuals that go with the flow. Have you heard of the
saying that "dead fish go with the flow"? This harsh reference contextualises
the notion of effort. Passengers in the tech can viewed as myriad of individuals
that are not necessarily involved in the disruption of the industry. They are
part of the audience. It is important to note that Passengers still retain much
responsibility and agency in this journey. Passengers can change trains, get off
and also change modes of transport i.e. this means that they also can choose
which apps are much useful to the society and which technologies should be
embraced and given room evolve. They are can also be seen as cheerleaders as
they provide insight on which technologies are interesting.

![Photo by Arūnas Naujokas on Unsplash](/images/apple-trees.jpg)

As the name suggests, this persona is quite self explanatory. ***Spectators***
are similar to passengers but relinquish their agency of choice and intuition to
the powers that may be. They are curious and are willing to take a risk by being
passively involved. They go with the flow. Spectators can bee seen as observers
or members of the audience, just like passengers. This means that they can still
have an opinion on the matter but their vested interest is not as strong. 

***Fruit-pickers*** are in-between the dreamers and moonshooters. They are
action-driven much like the moonshooters but they strive for simpler and more
efficient solutions with the resources that are within reach. If you think of a
fruit tree, it is much easier to take the ripe fruit that is on a lower branch
than it is getting the fruit at the top of the tree. Problems should be handled
in this manner, but you find, particularly in the tech industry, innovations to
pick the fruit at the top of the tree tend to materalise much more often than
simple solutions aimed to get the fruit at the top of the tree.

Read more on fruit-pickers in our previous article
[here.](./blog/the-low-end-theory/)

---
title: The Low End Theory
order: 0
author: Yeehaa
date: 2021-02-01
tags:
  - moonshots
  - exponentiality
  - entrepreneurship
  - low-hanging fruit
excerpt: |
  Everyone seems to be working on moonshots nowadays, because... well... Google
  does it. Google's approach is to take an unsolvable problem and pump a
  shitload of resources into it. Most others only copy the unsolvable problem
  bit.  True to it's cutting corner mindset, Lefthoek leaves shooting at moons
  to Google and its copy-cats and picks low-hanging fruit instead.
---

> There's a tidal wave of mysticism   
> Surging through our jet-aged generation   
> It's all designed to take us to the sky   
> 
> *Funkadelic*

In 2010, Google's Larry Page and Sergey Brin asked their buddy
[Astro](<https://hanna-barbera.fandom.com/wiki/Astro>) Teller to front an
experimental company builder mysteriously called [X](<https://x.company/>). The
single roman numeral signifies the almost religious belief in exponential logic
that both X and its mother company hold. X promises to only invest in ideas that
could make at least a 10x &mdash; Xx, get it?  &mdash; impact over the status
quo. 

The projects that X engages with are appropriately named
[moonshots](<https://www.thegeniusworks.com/2020/02/a-decade-of-moonshots-alphabet-x/>).
An term first introduced in Jules Verne's [From the Earth to the
Moon](<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/From_the_Earth_to_the_Moon>) but popularized
by president John F. Kennedy in 1961. In his famous speech, Kennedy promised
congress that he would get a man on the moon before the end of the decade.
Moreover, and equally important, the president also pledged to bring this man
back safely to earth.  Eight years and $25.4 billion dollars &mdash; that would
equate to $150 billion in today's economy &mdash; later, Apollo 11 managed to
fulfill that promise.

X takes this idea one step further by refering to itself as a moonshot factory.
The company doesn't just embark on nearly impossible missions, but aims to make
these journeys mass-producible. Its mission does not consist of solving one
*particular* impossible problem, but finding the recipe to solve *any*
impossible problem. X's blueprint for producing moonshots consists of three
simple, repeatable steps:

1. Focus on an unsolvable problem    

2. Spend a shitload of money on it  

3. Sell the resulting solution

Over a decade later, we can indisputably conclude that X's moonshot recipe has
lead to a massive amount of inspiring Wired covers. Whereas world's biggest
problems seem to be as unsolvable as 10 years ago. But hey, those [Google
Glasses](<https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/feb/19/google-glass-advice-smartglasses-glasshole#:~:text=Early%20adopters%20of%20Glass%2C%20derogatorily,for%20long%20periods%20of%20time.>)
do make you look cool while cruising your [Waymo](<https://waymo.com/>), right?

![Photo by Mariah Leynes @ Unsplash](/images/moonshot.jpg)


## Counterfeit Moon Shooters

> Rake in dividends   
> Let the money stack  
> See you copycats   
>
> *Brockhampton*

More impressive than the actual solutions that it has produced, may be the
amount of [copy cats](<https://www.moonshot-factory.eu/en/missions/>) that X has
inspired since then. Over the last decade, many an agency, incubator, or VC firm
has reinvented itself as a moonshot factory. 

While the marketing material of these counterfeit moon shooters was mostly
copied one-to-one from X's website, closer inspection reveals that they did in
fact made some small but significant changes to the original formula. In true
[Shenzen fashion](<https://nostarch.com/hardwarehackerpaperback>), they added a few features and removed some others.

1. Focus an fashionable problem    

2. Ask for a shitload of money 

As we speak, the tech world is overflowing with aspiring moon shooters searching
for generous sponsors and benevolent donors. Entrepreneurs no longer look for
investors to fund their solutions. Instead, they look for those that will let
them solve the world biggest problems. Give these aspiring Elon Musks enough
money and they will cure cancer, stop famine, and end poverty. Or so they claim.
Humanity and humility share little more than a few common letters.

![Photo by NASA @ Unsplash](/images/moonshot-2.jpg)

## Flying Low
 
> So low-key that you probably missed it   
> And yet it's so loud    
> That it stands in the crowd
>
> *A Tribe Called Quest*

Lefthoek consciously chooses not to aim for the moon. We leave pride and glory
for others, and are perfectly satisfied to do the things that need to be done
and no one else seems to care about. Moreover, we are commited to solve them
with the simplest technology possible. 

Lefthoek loves low-hanging fruit: the lower the fruit, the sweeter the juice. In
everyday tasks, there are so many small problems that could make your work a
more fun and satisfying. These could be things like:

+ Onboarding a new staff member that feels lost at the new job

+ Storing and retrieving all the interesting links that your team members shared 

+ Summarize all the messages that you missed during your vacation

Lefhoek is dedicated to solving all of these issues and many more, one at a
time: by as few means possible. That, in short, is what *the low end theory* is
all about.

I quit my job. Convinced that education was the next industry that was going to be disrupted. And Offcourse was ready to shake it up.

But starting a business alone was not enough of a challenge. So I decided to make it a bit harder for myself. Just making money was too mundane. My company, no my initiative, no my movement, would be so much more than that.

Offcourse needed to be:
- Value-driven
- Open-Source
- Nonprofit
- Community Driven
- Bootstrapped
- Bla Bla Bla

I now realize that without a working business model, my so-called ethics were nothing but an opinion. And we all know how the famous saying about opinions goes.

Put differently, I forgot to stay true to my corner-cutting self. The optimal way to achieve your goal is the one that delivers the best results with the least amount of effort.
